body:
there are lint errors.  One thing that I think we still need to fix is using function id instead of name, to avoid dict lookup in each function call. Specifically, we can have a global table and at startup do

ecall_register(const char* name, int func_id);

so the module knows the name-> func_id mapping, when we do the call, the internal can just use the func_id(with boundary check) to lookup the functions

I have some questions.
For the case in this PR,
before split, the lower code is
```
produce T {
  for (i, 0, 1024) {
    T.v0[i] = -1
    T.v1[i] = -340282346638528859811704183484516925440.000000f
    for (k, 0, 1024) {
      T.v0[i] = tvm_if_then_else((T.v1[i] < A[((i*1024) + k)]), k, T.v0[i])
      T.v1[i] = tvm_if_then_else((T.v1[i] < A[((i*1024) + k)]), A[((i*1024) + k)], T.v1[i])
    }
  }
}
```
before tensorize, 
```
produce T {
  for (i.outer, 0, 256) {
    for (i.inner.init, 0, 4) {
      T.v0[((i.outer*4) + i.inner.init)] = -1
      T.v1[((i.outer*4) + i.inner.init)] = -340282346638528859811704183484516925440.000000f
    }
    for (k.outer, 0, 64) {
      for (i.inner, 0, 4) {
        for (k.inner, 0, 16) {
          T.v0[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)] = tvm_if_then_else((T.v1[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)] < A[(((((i.outer*256) + k.outer) + (i.inner*64))*16) + k.inner)]), ((k.outer*16) + k.inner), T.v0[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)])
          T.v1[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)] = tvm_if_then_else((T.v1[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)] < A[(((((i.outer*256) + k.outer) + (i.inner*64))*16) + k.inner)]), A[(((((i.outer*256) + k.outer) + (i.inner*64))*16) + k.inner)], T.v1[((i.outer*4) + i.inner)])
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
Notice that, in ComputeOpNode self->axis what we have are still axis before split, i, k. also the same for out_dom.
 IMO, the body need to be tensorized should be split code, that is to say, what we have in ComputeOpNode::axis and out_dom should be axis after splitting, like k.inner k.outer i.inner i.outer. anything wrong with it?
Anyway what's the meaning of out_dom and in_dom?

